{"id":120,"date":"2021-10-01T00:00:08","date_gmt":"2021-10-01T00:00:08","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/127.0.0.1:10080\/wordpress\/?p=120"},"modified":"2022-02-28T19:35:52","modified_gmt":"2022-02-28T19:35:52","slug":"black-lives-matter-acdc","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"http:\/\/127.0.0.1:10080\/wordpress\/2021\/black-lives-matter-acdc\/","title":{"rendered":"Black Lives Matter @ ACDC"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns alignfull main-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\">\n<p>a proposed mural<br>made in Illustrator and Photoshop<br>fall 2021<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>High up and across from the Atlanta City Detention Center lies a vent-lined wall on MARTA&#8217;s Garnett station. Here, I place a mural with an aggressive but simplistic message, with the hope that it may be visible by prisoners through the small slitted windows available in the building. Black Lives Matter, a popular phrase and hashtag encompassing the modern grief of Black people in the face police brutality, is written with a bold but handwriting-esque font. The iconic raised fists are shackled by handcuffs with breaking chains. This creates a call to action of breaking literal and metaphorical chains, urging both prisoners to stand up for themselves and onlookers to help break down the prison industrial complex. Furthermore, as a political message, I chose to give the mural a more graffiti and spray paint-esque look, as opposed to the clean lines more represented on positive, uplifting murals.<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\">\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-1 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><a href=\"http:\/\/127.0.0.1:10080\/wordpress\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/CNM-blmmural-final.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1024\" height=\"441\" src=\"http:\/\/127.0.0.1:10080\/wordpress\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/CNM-blmmural-final-1024x441.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"121\" data-full-url